            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is cloud computing?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Cloud computing is the delivery of computing services (servers, storage, databases, networking, software) over the internet on a pay-as-you-go basis, enabling flexible resources without local hardware.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'Define an algorithm.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'An algorithm is a finite, ordered set of well-defined instructions designed to solve a problem or accomplish a task within a finite amount of time.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a firewall?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A firewall is a security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on predefined security rules to protect a network from unauthorized access.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between hardware and software?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Hardware refers to the physical components of a computer (CPU, RAM, keyboard), while software is the set of programs and operating instructions that run on hardware.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is an IP address?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'An IP address is a unique numerical label assigned to each device on a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication and identification.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a database?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A database is an organized collection of structured data stored electronically, managed by a DBMS to allow efficient storage, retrieval, and manipulation of data.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'Define machine learning.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Machine learning is a subset of artificial intelligence where systems learn from data to improve their performance on tasks without being explicitly programmed.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is an operating system?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'An operating system is system software that manages computer hardware and software resources, providing common services for computer programs (e.g., Windows, Linux, macOS).','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between TCP and UDP?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'TCP is connection-oriented and ensures reliable, ordered data delivery. UDP is connectionless and faster but does not guarantee delivery.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is encryption?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Encryption is the process of converting readable data (plaintext) into an unreadable format (ciphertext) using an algorithm and key to protect information from unauthorized access.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between a process and a thread?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A process is an independent program in execution with its own memory space. A thread is a lighter unit of execution within a process, sharing memory with other threads in the same process.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'Define bandwidth.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Bandwidth is the maximum rate of data transfer across a network path, measured in bits per second (bps). It determines how much data can be sent in a given time period.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is virtualization in computing?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Virtualization is the creation of virtual versions of physical resources using software, allowing multiple virtual machines to run on a single physical machine.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a deadlock in operating systems?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A deadlock occurs when two or more processes are blocked forever, each waiting for a resource held by the other, resulting in a circular dependency with no progress.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between a compiler and an interpreter?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A compiler translates the entire source code into machine code before execution. An interpreter translates and executes code line by line at runtime without producing a separate executable.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'Define Big Data and its 3 Vs.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Big Data refers to extremely large datasets. The 3 Vs are: Volume (massive data size), Velocity (speed of generation/processing), and Variety (different data types).','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a VPN?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A VPN (Virtual Private Network) creates an encrypted tunnel over the internet, allowing users to send and receive data as if connected to a private network, ensuring privacy and security.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the role of a switch in a network?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A switch connects devices within a LAN and uses MAC addresses to forward data to the correct device, operating at the Data Link layer (Layer 2) of the OSI model.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between HTTP and HTTPS?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'HTTP transmits data in plain text without encryption. HTTPS adds SSL/TLS encryption, ensuring data confidentiality and integrity between browser and server.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a denial-of-service (DoS) attack?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A DoS attack floods a server or network with excessive requests, overwhelming its resources and making it unavailable to legitimate users.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is version control?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Version control is a system that records changes to files over time, allowing developers to track history, revert to previous versions, and collaborate without overwriting each other\'s work.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is multitasking in an operating system?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Multitasking is the OS\'s ability to execute multiple processes concurrently by rapidly switching between them, giving the illusion they run simultaneously on a single CPU.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is an API gateway?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'An API gateway is a server that acts as the entry point for client requests, routing them to appropriate microservices, handling authentication, rate limiting, and load balancing.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of recursion.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Recursion is a programming technique where a function calls itself with a smaller input until a base condition is met. It simplifies complex problems like factorial computation and tree traversal.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is load balancing?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Load balancing distributes incoming network traffic across multiple servers to ensure no single server is overwhelmed, improving availability, reliability, and performance.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a cache in computing?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A cache is a small, fast memory that stores frequently accessed data temporarily so future requests can be served faster, reducing access time to slower storage.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is responsive web design?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Responsive web design makes web pages render well on all devices and screen sizes by using flexible grids, fluid images, and CSS media queries.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is containerization in software deployment?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Containerization packages an application and its dependencies into a portable container (e.g., Docker), ensuring consistent behavior across different environments.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is DevOps?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'DevOps combines software development and IT operations, emphasizing automation, continuous integration/delivery, and collaboration to shorten development cycles.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the role of middleware?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Middleware is software that connects different applications or systems, facilitating communication and data management between them (e.g., message queues, API layers).','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is edge computing?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Edge computing processes data near the source (edge devices) rather than sending it to a central cloud server, reducing latency and bandwidth usage for IoT and real-time applications.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a stack overflow error?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A stack overflow occurs when a program\'s call stack exceeds its allocated memory, typically caused by infinite or deeply nested recursion, causing the program to crash.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous programming?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Synchronous programming executes tasks sequentially — each operation must complete before the next begins. Asynchronous programming allows operations (e.g., I/O) to run in the background, enabling other code to execute without waiting.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a RESTful API?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A RESTful API follows REST (Representational State Transfer) constraints: statelessness, client-server architecture, uniform interface, and resource-based URLs. It uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) to perform CRUD operations.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between stack and heap memory?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Stack memory is automatically managed, stores local variables and function calls (LIFO), and is limited in size. Heap memory is dynamically allocated at runtime for objects, managed manually or by garbage collection, and is larger but slower.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'Define a protocol in networking.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A network protocol is a set of rules and conventions that govern how data is transmitted between devices, defining format, timing, sequencing, and error handling (e.g., TCP/IP, HTTP, FTP).','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a hash function?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A hash function maps input data of arbitrary size to a fixed-size output (hash/digest). It is deterministic, one-way, and collision-resistant. Used in password storage, data integrity verification, and digital signatures (e.g., SHA-256).','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is Docker and why is it used?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Docker is a containerization platform that packages applications and their dependencies into lightweight containers. It ensures consistent behavior across development, testing, and production environments, simplifying deployment and scaling.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a relational schema?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A relational schema defines the structure of a database including table names, column names, data types, and constraints (primary keys, foreign keys). It is the logical blueprint for organizing relational data.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is two-factor authentication (2FA)?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'2FA is a security mechanism requiring users to provide two distinct forms of identification: something they know (password), something they have (OTP token), or something they are (biometric), reducing unauthorized access risk.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a race condition and how can it be prevented?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A race condition occurs when the outcome of a program depends on unpredictable execution order of concurrent operations. Prevention: use synchronization mechanisms such as mutexes, semaphores, or atomic operations to control access to shared resources.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between RAM and ROM?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'RAM (Random Access Memory) is volatile, read-write memory used for temporary data during program execution. ROM (Read-Only Memory) is non-volatile, stores firmware permanently, and retains data without power.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the purpose of a foreign key in a relational database?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A foreign key is a column that references the primary key of another table, enforcing referential integrity by ensuring that a value in one table corresponds to an existing value in the referenced table.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a denial-of-service (DDoS) attack and how does it differ from DoS?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A DoS attack originates from a single source flooding a server. A DDoS (Distributed DoS) uses multiple compromised machines (botnets) to simultaneously flood the target, making it harder to block since traffic comes from many IPs.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the purpose of indexing in a database?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'An index creates a separate data structure (B-tree or hash) that allows the database engine to locate records quickly without scanning entire tables, dramatically improving SELECT query performance at the cost of additional storage.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between a hub, switch, and router?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A hub broadcasts to all ports (Layer 1). A switch uses MAC addresses to forward data to specific ports (Layer 2). A router directs traffic between different networks using IP addresses (Layer 3), connecting LANs to the internet.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a REST endpoint?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A REST endpoint is a specific URL in a RESTful API that represents a resource and responds to HTTP methods. For example, GET /users returns all users, POST /users creates one, and DELETE /users/{id} removes a specific user.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is a boolean data type?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'A boolean is a primitive data type that represents only two values: true or false (1 or 0). It is fundamental to conditional logic, comparisons, and control flow in virtually all programming languages.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is software testing and why is it important?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Software testing is the process of evaluating a program to detect defects, verify it meets requirements, and ensure quality. It reduces bugs, improves security, builds user trust, and lowers maintenance costs. Types include unit, integration, system, and acceptance testing.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'short_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between authentication and authorization?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Authentication verifies the identity of a user (who you are), typically via passwords or biometrics. Authorization determines what an authenticated user is permitted to do (what you can access). Authentication always precedes authorization.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],

            // =========================================================
            // ICT — LONG QUESTIONS (Q112–Q132) 30
            // =========================================================
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the OSI model and describe the function of each layer.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'The OSI model is a 7-layer framework: (1) Physical — transmits raw bits; (2) Data Link — error-free transfer between adjacent nodes; (3) Network — routing and logical addressing (IP); (4) Transport — end-to-end communication, TCP/UDP; (5) Session — manages sessions; (6) Presentation — translates, encrypts, compresses data; (7) Application — interfaces with end-user software (HTTP, FTP, DNS). Each layer serves the one above and is served by the one below.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Compare and contrast structured and unstructured data with examples.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Structured data is organized in rows and columns (e.g., relational databases, spreadsheets) — easy to search using SQL. Unstructured data has no predefined format (e.g., emails, images, videos) — requires AI/NLP to analyze. Semi-structured data (JSON, XML) lies between both. Roughly 80% of enterprise data is unstructured.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the evolution of the internet from Web 1.0 to Web 3.0.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Web 1.0 (1990s): static, read-only pages. Web 2.0 (2000s–present): interactive/social web — users create content (YouTube, Facebook). Web 3.0: emerging decentralized web using blockchain, AI, semantic data — enabling data ownership and decentralized apps (dApps). Key differences: interactivity, ownership, and decentralization.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of Object-Oriented Programming and its four pillars.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'OOP is based on objects combining data and behavior. The four pillars: (1) Encapsulation — bundling data and methods in a class; (2) Abstraction — hiding complexity, exposing interfaces; (3) Inheritance — child class inherits from parent; (4) Polymorphism — same interface, different implementations. OOP improves modularity, reusability, and maintainability.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Describe different types of cybersecurity threats and prevention methods.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Threats: Malware (viruses, ransomware), Phishing (deceptive emails), Man-in-the-Middle (intercepting communications), DDoS (traffic flooding), SQL Injection (malicious database queries), Zero-day exploits. Prevention: firewalls, antivirus, encryption, multi-factor authentication, regular patching, security awareness training, and intrusion detection systems.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concepts of Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, and Deep Learning and their relationships.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'AI is the broad field of simulating human intelligence. ML is a subset of AI where algorithms learn from data. Deep Learning is a subset of ML using multi-layered neural networks excelling at image recognition and NLP. Relationship: AI ⊇ ML ⊇ DL. DL powers GPT, AlphaGo, and image classifiers, transforming healthcare, finance, and autonomous vehicles.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the importance of data security and privacy in modern digital systems.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Data security protects information via the CIA triad: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. Privacy ensures individuals control personal data, governed by GDPR and similar regulations. Organizations must implement encryption, access controls, auditing, and breach notification. Cloud computing and IoT amplify these challenges significantly.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'What is the difference between public cloud, private cloud, and hybrid cloud?','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Public cloud (AWS, Azure): third-party owned, scalable, cost-efficient but less control. Private cloud: organization-hosted, maximum security and control, higher cost. Hybrid cloud: combines both, keeping sensitive data private while using public cloud for scale. Choice depends on data sensitivity, budget, compliance, and workload patterns.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) and its phases.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'SDLC phases: (1) Planning — scope and feasibility; (2) Requirements Analysis — functional/non-functional requirements; (3) System Design — architecture and UI; (4) Implementation — coding; (5) Testing — unit, integration, UAT; (6) Deployment — production release; (7) Maintenance — bug fixes and updates. Models include Waterfall (sequential) and Agile (iterative sprints).','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the role of Artificial Intelligence in healthcare.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'AI applications in healthcare: diagnostics (medical image analysis), drug discovery (reducing years to months), personalized medicine, predictive analytics (outbreak forecasting), virtual health assistants, and robot-assisted surgery. Challenges include data privacy, algorithmic bias, regulatory approval, and need for clinical validation.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the differences between procedural and object-oriented programming with examples.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Procedural programming structures code as procedures/functions with data and functions separate (e.g., C with calculateSalary()). OOP organizes code around objects encapsulating data and behavior (e.g., Java Employee class with salary attributes and calculateBonus()). OOP excels in large, complex systems through inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Compare relational and non-relational databases, providing use cases for each.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Relational (MySQL, PostgreSQL): structured tables, predefined schema, SQL queries, ACID transactions — ideal for banking, ERP, e-commerce. Non-relational (MongoDB, Cassandra): flexible schema, horizontal scaling, unstructured data — ideal for social media, real-time analytics, IoT. Modern apps often use polyglot persistence combining both.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of Big Data and discuss the technologies used to process it.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Big Data: datasets too large for traditional tools, defined by 5 Vs (Volume, Velocity, Variety, Veracity, Value). Technologies: Hadoop (HDFS + MapReduce), Apache Spark (in-memory), Kafka (streaming), Hive (SQL on Hadoop), NoSQL databases. Applications: fraud detection, recommendations, social media analysis, smart cities.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss cybersecurity frameworks and their role in protecting organizations.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Key frameworks: NIST CSF (Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover), ISO/IEC 27001 (information security management), CIS Controls (prioritized defenses), COBIT (IT governance). Benefits: standardized risk management, compliance (GDPR, HIPAA), structured incident response. Implementation: risk assessment, gap analysis, control selection, continuous monitoring.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the importance of the Internet of Things (IoT) and the challenges it presents.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'IoT connects physical devices via internet for data exchange. Benefits: smart homes, healthcare monitoring, smart cities, industrial automation, precision agriculture. Challenges: security (weak credentials, large attack surface), privacy (continuous collection), interoperability, scalability, power consumption, and real-time data management addressed by edge computing.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the impact of social media on privacy and data security.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Social media collects location, preferences, behavior, and contacts. Risks: data harvesting, third-party app access, account hacking, doxxing, surveillance capitalism (Cambridge Analytica case). Mitigation: GDPR compliance, data minimization, user consent, privacy settings, and digital literacy education.','difficulty_level'=>'easy','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the principles of ethical hacking and penetration testing.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Ethical hacking is authorized cyberattack simulation to find vulnerabilities. Principles: written permission, defined scope, non-disclosure, detailed reporting. Phases: Reconnaissance, Scanning, Exploitation, Post-Exploitation, Reporting. Types: white-box, black-box, grey-box. Tools: Nmap, Metasploit, Wireshark, Burp Suite. Certification: CEH.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the role of microservices architecture in modern software development.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Microservices decompose an application into small, independently deployable services. Benefits: independent scaling, technology flexibility, fault isolation, and faster deployment cycles. Challenges: distributed system complexity, inter-service communication (REST/gRPC), data consistency, and observability. Tools: Docker, Kubernetes, API gateways. Contrast with monolithic architecture.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss quantum computing and its potential impact on cybersecurity.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Quantum computing uses qubits in superposition and entanglement for exponentially faster computation. Threat: Shor\'s algorithm can break RSA and ECC encryption. Opportunity: Quantum Key Distribution (QKD) enables theoretically unbreakable encryption. Post-quantum cryptography standards (NIST FIPS 203/204) are being adopted. Timeline for cryptographically relevant quantum computers: estimated 10–20 years.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the MVC design pattern and why it is widely used in web development.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'MVC separates application into: Model (data and business logic), View (user interface), Controller (handles input, updates Model/View). Benefits: separation of concerns, easier testing, parallel development, and reusability. Used in Laravel (PHP), Django (Python), Ruby on Rails, and ASPoint.NET MVC. It reduces coupling between UI and business logic, making applications maintainable at scale.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of blockchain technology and its applications beyond cryptocurrency.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Blockchain is a distributed, immutable ledger where transactions are recorded in chronologically linked blocks secured by cryptographic hashes. Key properties: decentralization (no single authority), transparency, immutability, and consensus mechanisms (Proof of Work, Proof of Stake). Beyond cryptocurrency: (1) Supply chain transparency — tracking goods from origin to consumer (Walmart, Maersk); (2) Healthcare — secure patient record sharing; (3) Smart contracts — self-executing agreements on Ethereum; (4) Voting systems — tamper-proof digital elections; (5) NFTs — digital ownership verification; (6) Land registries — fraud-resistant property records. Challenges: scalability (Bitcoin processes ~7 TPS vs Visa\'s 24,000), energy consumption, regulatory uncertainty, and interoperability between chains.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the principles and importance of software testing, including different testing types.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Software testing verifies that a system meets requirements and is free of critical defects. Key principles: testing shows presence of defects (not absence), exhaustive testing is impossible, early testing saves cost, defects cluster in modules, and tests must evolve. Types: (1) Unit Testing — individual functions/modules; (2) Integration Testing — interaction between modules; (3) System Testing — complete system validation; (4) Acceptance Testing (UAT) — client verification; (5) Regression Testing — ensuring changes do not break existing features; (6) Performance Testing — load, stress, scalability; (7) Security Testing — vulnerability identification. Methodologies: black-box (functional), white-box (structural), grey-box. Modern practices: TDD (Test-Driven Development), BDD, CI/CD pipelines with automated test suites.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of operating system scheduling algorithms and compare them.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'CPU scheduling allocates processor time to processes. Algorithms: (1) FCFS (First Come First Served) — simple, non-preemptive, suffers from convoy effect; (2) SJF (Shortest Job First) — optimal average waiting time but requires knowing burst time; (3) Round Robin — preemptive, each process gets a fixed time quantum, fair for time-sharing; (4) Priority Scheduling — higher priority runs first, risk of starvation mitigated by aging; (5) Multilevel Queue — separate queues for foreground/background processes; (6) Multilevel Feedback Queue — most complex, processes move between queues based on behavior. Metrics: CPU utilization, throughput, turnaround time, waiting time, response time. Modern OS (Linux CFS) use weighted fair scheduling for balance.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the architecture and components of a modern web application.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Modern web apps follow a multi-tier architecture: (1) Client (Frontend) — browser renders HTML/CSS/JavaScript; frameworks: React, Vue, Angular; (2) Backend/API — server-side logic via REST or GraphQL APIs; frameworks: Laravel, Django, Express, Spring; (3) Database — relational (MySQL) for structured data, NoSQL (MongoDB) for flexible data; (4) Cache — Redis/Memcached for fast data retrieval; (5) CDN — static asset delivery; (6) Authentication — JWT, OAuth 2.0; (7) Message Queues — RabbitMQ, Kafka for async processing; (8) Load Balancer — distributes traffic; (9) Cloud Infrastructure — AWS, GCP, Azure with auto-scaling. Security considerations: HTTPS, input validation, CSRF protection, rate limiting. DevOps: CI/CD pipelines, Docker, Kubernetes for deployment.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain data structures and algorithms and why they are fundamental to software engineering.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Data structures organize and store data for efficient access and modification. Key structures: Arrays (O(1) random access), Linked Lists (O(1) insertion), Stacks (LIFO, function calls), Queues (FIFO, scheduling), Hash Tables (O(1) average lookup), Trees (hierarchical data, BST for search), Graphs (networks, shortest path). Algorithms solve computational problems: Sorting (Merge Sort O(n log n), Quick Sort), Searching (Binary Search O(log n)), Graph traversal (BFS, DFS), Dynamic Programming (optimal substructure), Greedy Algorithms. Importance: efficient algorithms reduce time/space complexity, enabling systems to scale. A poorly chosen algorithm can make a feature unusable (O(n²) vs O(n log n) on millions of records). Mastery is essential for technical interviews and engineering large-scale systems.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Describe the principles of network security and the main techniques used to secure networks.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Network security protects infrastructure from unauthorized access, misuse, and attacks. Core principles: CIA triad (Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability) + Authentication, Non-repudiation. Techniques: (1) Firewalls — packet filtering, stateful inspection, application-layer; (2) IDS/IPS — detect and prevent intrusions; (3) VPN — encrypted tunnels for remote access; (4) Encryption — TLS for data in transit, AES for data at rest; (5) DMZ — isolated zone for public-facing servers; (6) Network segmentation — VLANs limit blast radius; (7) Zero Trust Architecture — never trust, always verify; (8) Multi-Factor Authentication; (9) Security audits and penetration testing; (10) Security Information and Event Management (SIEM). Threats defended: MITM, DDoS, packet sniffing, ARP spoofing, DNS poisoning.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of virtualization and how it differs from containerization.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Virtualization creates virtual machines (VMs) using a hypervisor (Type 1: VMware ESXi, Hyper-V; Type 2: VirtualBox). Each VM includes a full OS kernel, making it heavyweight (GBs) but fully isolated. Containerization (Docker, Podman) shares the host OS kernel, packaging only the app and dependencies in lightweight containers (MBs), starting in seconds. Comparison: VMs offer stronger isolation but use more resources; containers are faster, more portable, and efficient. Orchestration: Kubernetes manages containers at scale. Use cases: VMs for different OS requirements or strong security isolation; containers for microservices, CI/CD pipelines, and cloud-native apps. Hybrid: VMs run container clusters for layered security.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the impact of artificial intelligence on employment and the future of work.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'AI automates routine cognitive and physical tasks, displacing roles in manufacturing, data entry, customer service, and basic legal/medical analysis. McKinsey estimates 15-30% of current tasks could be automated by 2030. New roles created: AI trainers, prompt engineers, data scientists, AI ethicists, and automation specialists. Historical pattern: past industrial revolutions eliminated roles but created new industries (internet created millions of jobs). Key concerns: job displacement concentration in lower-income workers, skills gap, geographic inequality, and the pace of change exceeding workforce adaptation. Solutions: reskilling programs, lifelong learning culture, STEM education, UBI pilots, and government policy frameworks. Net impact is debated but structural adjustment is certain, requiring proactive social and educational policy.','difficulty_level'=>'medium','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Explain the concept of computer memory hierarchy and its importance in system performance.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Memory hierarchy organizes storage from fastest/smallest/costliest to slowest/largest/cheapest: (1) CPU Registers — picoseconds, bytes; (2) L1 Cache — 1-4 cycles, 32-64KB per core; (3) L2 Cache — 4-12 cycles, 256KB–1MB; (4) L3 Cache — 10-40 cycles, 4-64MB shared; (5) RAM — 60-100ns, GBs; (6) SSD — 0.1ms, TBs; (7) HDD — 5-10ms, TBs; (8) Optical/Tape — seconds, archival. Locality principles: temporal locality (recently used data reused) and spatial locality (nearby data accessed). Cache hit/miss rates dramatically affect performance — a cache miss penalty can cost 200+ cycles. Design strategies: prefetching, cache-aware algorithms, memory pooling. Understanding hierarchy is essential for writing high-performance software and database query optimization.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],
            ['topic'=>'ICT','question_type'=>'long_question','question_text'=>'Discuss the principles of clean code and software design patterns.','option_a'=>null,'option_b'=>null,'option_c'=>null,'option_d'=>null,'correct_answer'=>'Clean code (Robert C. Martin) is readable, maintainable, and expressive: meaningful names, small focused functions, no duplication (DRY), minimal comments (self-documenting code), and consistent formatting. SOLID principles: (S) Single Responsibility, (O) Open/Closed, (L) Liskov Substitution, (I) Interface Segregation, (D) Dependency Inversion. Design Patterns (Gang of Four): Creational (Singleton, Factory, Builder), Structural (Adapter, Decorator, Facade), Behavioral (Observer, Strategy, Command). Anti-patterns to avoid: God Object, Spaghetti Code, Magic Numbers, Copy-Paste Programming. Code smells: long methods, large classes, feature envy, data clumps. Refactoring addresses smells without changing behavior. Clean code reduces technical debt, onboarding time, and bug rates significantly in long-term projects.','difficulty_level'=>'hard','marks'=>1.00],

